"Yes, captain. They must be on their way now, we've given them time to get rations from the mess." At 5:00 sharp, Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle parking area. Shaw got up on a crate and began to speak.
"We're deploying to FOB I-131, about 80 kilometers from Ianlos. We've got to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we'll have a forward position and a foothold at the foot of the mountains," Shaw explained. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each man returning to his unit, and the sergeants made them board the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side, his legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, has Harris always had Snowball?", Nemic asked as they were getting settled.
"Are you talking about the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure".
Cohren cast a glance towards one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken flapping its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yes, he always had it", Cohren replied as the tank turret swung open with a clink to let his commander pass.
"All the tanks were on the move," calmly declared, but clearly the commander in his helmet. The engines of a tank platoon and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos on which Cohren was located had a jolt when its brakes were released and it moved to take formation. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
About an hour later, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, haven't you?"
"Uh-huh, Operation Thunderfire," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd have it wrapped up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Downplaying it is an understatement," Nemic says, joining in on the conversation. "They had more guns and people than we anticipated. They managed to take down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus, last month. Shit, we should have seen this coming from the road we're on."
"Well, I'll be fine for the Federation," said Orson with a bit of provocation. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You're saying that now, but from experience, I know that 18-year-old new recruits like you take cover as soon as they hear a shot," Craith declared.
"I think we'll soon have it settled," Corhen said, laughing. Orson did not follow up on the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO", crackled Cohren's radio. "We're detecting thermal signatures approximately 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren boosted himself up to the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. By activating thermal vision, he could see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them", Cohren replied via his throat mic.
"Any enemies?", asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"It's impossible to say", Cohren declared. He activated his microphone and said: "Exodus company, don't fire unless they fire on you, let them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures changed from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they drew closer, one of them ran towards something, grabbed it, then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took firing position.
"We have contact," Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the crest. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, as the soldiers leapt from the vehicles to take cover behind them. A tank-killing missile whizzed by and slammed into the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris flying onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew extracted themselves and dived to take cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2, take 1-2 and 1-3 left, 25 degrees right, 275 meters." "Fire," yelled the commander of the tank platoon into the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew towards the ridge and exploded, projecting mud and rocks into the air.
"Send the Sentis", Knoxx cried, observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet stepped out. He bellowed orders into a square microphone and two Sentis, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed out. Their thin metal arms and legs swayed forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their arms were attached to their backs.
"Kill them or capture them?", Craith asked as they watched.
"It would seem that we catch them", Cohren advanced as the two Sentinels disappeared in a cloud of ash and smoke. Cries and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but ceased quickly. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots trailed on the ground. Once in safety with the squad, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he fell into the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the individual, who was starting to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," said the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw shook his head and turned towards Cohren and Craith, who stood beside him. "Both of you, would you have the kindness to get rid of this man?"
